Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-03-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Erroneous and misleading information about Synonymous SNPs (sSNPs).
Input.posts:
Sorry I'm late, but I've started the course just 3 days ago. Eventhough it already has a post relating this, it does not really seems to put the attention that this subject deserves. In lecture slides page 6: 'Synonymous substitutions are not exposed...' I suggest that this information has to be changed. According to Chen (2010) (DOI:10.1371/journal.pone.0013574) sSNPs are just as likely to be involved in disease mechanisms. The reason of this is really well explained in a Nature paper of 2011 by Sauna and Kimchi-Sarfaty (DOI:10.1038/nrg3051) where they describe 4 different reasons why exactly sSNPs might be as damaging as the nsSNPs. (short link for the paper: http://goo.gl/CFy1Sf , reasons really well summarized on page 686 Figure 1). Therefore, nowadays, to stating that 'Synonymous substitutions are not exposed to (strong) selective pressures since they don’t result in a change to the protein sequence' and to suggest that this type of method would bring a more reliable result, would be as we Brazilians call: 'a shot in the foot'.
Upvotes:
2
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Yes, I am aware of this, Rodrigo, and it is a good point, but I didn't want to go into so much detail. I will update for the next iteration of the course. Other papers are Agashe et al. (2013, MBE), Gu et al. (2012, MBE), Zhou et al. (2013, Nature). Best, Nick
Instructor's post : Yes, I am aware of this, Rodrigo, and it is a good point, but I didn't want to go into so much detail. I will update for the next iteration of the course. Other papers are Agashe et al. (2013, MBE), Gu et al. (2012, MBE), Zhou et al. (2013, Nature). Best, Nick

3

Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-03-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Sign of Selection
Input.posts:
Hi, all. I'll just post some quots from the lecture5. > 'Positive (“Darwinian”) selection occurs when a beneficial mutation occurs in a population and increases in frequency (e.g. antibiotic resistance)' > 'Positive selection effectively sweeps genetic variation from a population' > 'In the case of positive selection, you would expect to see a higher proportion of amino acid substitutions in your population (because they are being increased by positive selection)' I can see certain inconsistency or even contradiction here. Clarification required.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Over all alleles, the genetic variation surrounding the site that is beneficial would typically be synonymous in nature for coding sequences, Anon. Thus if the beneficial allele is retained, those alleles with (synonymous) variation surrounding the selected site would be lost (the beneficial mutation is presumably non-synonymous in nature), and then your Ka/Ks ratio'd be positive. Make sense? Best, Nick
Instructor's post : Over all alleles, the genetic variation surrounding the site that is beneficial would typically be synonymous in nature for coding sequences, Anon. Thus if the beneficial allele is retained, those alleles with (synonymous) variation surrounding the selected site would be lost (the beneficial mutation is presumably non-synonymous in nature), and then your Ka/Ks ratio'd be positive. Make sense? Best, Nick

Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-03-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Sign of Selection
Input.posts:
Hi, all. I'll just post some quots from the lecture5. > 'Positive (“Darwinian”) selection occurs when a beneficial mutation occurs in a population and increases in frequency (e.g. antibiotic resistance)' > 'Positive selection effectively sweeps genetic variation from a population' > 'In the case of positive selection, you would expect to see a higher proportion of amino acid substitutions in your population (because they are being increased by positive selection)' I can see certain inconsistency or even contradiction here. Clarification required.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Over all alleles, the genetic variation surrounding the site that is beneficial would typically be synonymous in nature for coding sequences, Anon. Thus if the beneficial allele is retained, those alleles with (synonymous) variation surrounding the selected site would be lost (the beneficial mutation is presumably non-synonymous in nature), and then your Ka/Ks ratio'd be positive. Make sense? Best, Nick
Instructor's post : Over all alleles, the genetic variation surrounding the site that is beneficial would typically be synonymous in nature for coding sequences, Anon. Thus if the beneficial allele is retained, those alleles with (synonymous) variation surrounding the selected site would be lost (the beneficial mutation is presumably non-synonymous in nature), and then your Ka/Ks ratio'd be positive. Make sense? Best, Nick

Input.threadtitle: When in relation to the three types of sections does non-synonymous/ synonymous mutations occur
Input.posts:
Is it write to argue that synonymous mutations may only occur in a balancing selection whilst, non-synonymous mutations only occur in +ve or -ve selections?
Upvotes:
0
Organisms tend to use some codons more than others, and other organisms prefer different ones, even if they code for the same amino acid.This is known as codon bias.So, even synonymous changes can be under (weaker) selective pressure. Also, a non-synonymous mutation could have little to no impact on fitness, but might increase in frequency due to random drift.
Upvotes:
0
='Is it write to argue that synonymous mutations may only occur in a balancing selection' If I understood question correctly - no, it's not right. Synonymous mutations occur constantly, because they are under almost zero selection pressure.
Upvotes:
0
The effects of changing to synonymous\xA0codons might be subtle, but it seems they aren't insignificant: see e.g.\xA0 http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21102527 http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18983258 http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20308095 http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9720271
